pr_body:
Decided to try myself in Android Auto.

I checked `android_auto` branch and want to thank @shankarpriyank for the work. I had a good hint at start üòÄ 

What was done:
* Created separate `car` product flavor
   I know about the `minSdkVersion` restriction for Android Auto. That is why I think separate flavor is a good solution. There will be no problems during releases as no code and resources will be added to the release apk. It could be easily merged to the `master` branch and this would be a good place to start for a lot of people who wanted to contribute for android auto (I saw many messages in related issues).
   I also found that there is a possibility (at least at play store) for publishing separate apks for different APIs. So, I think there will be no problems in future to publish apk for API 21 without Android Auto and apk for API 23+ with Android Auto.
* All `car` related code and resources are located in `android/flavors/car`. As I said before, there will be no impact on release builds and almost no impact on current code base.
* Refactored `app/organicmaps/MapFragment.java`
  I moved all common logic for mobile and car into a separate `Map.java` class and also renamed `MapFragment.cpp` into `Map.cpp`
* I saw comments that there are some problems with Vulkan on Auto but for now it looks ok, I didn't change it to OpenGL.
* Created base navigation interface and some buttons for auto

I see two main parts you may want to discuss:
* `build.gradle` - new flavor "approach"
* `MapFragment.java` - refactoring

Main things that should be done next (or not working now) (in this PR on in separate ones):
* Update GitHub Actions config as product flavor names changed
* To prohibit opening application on mobile phone when it is run on Android Auto (like in Google Maps)
* You may see on the video when moving map it sometimes scales. It should be fixed, but I don't know how to do it yet.
* To add current position on the map. I also don't know how it works yet
* Implement UI `onFling` event
* ...
* That's all for now but I may add something more later

And here is the video with the demonstration:
https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/10351358/199609542-514e0ce5-a8ae-45f2-a806-780bb79ff903.mp4

See #679

pr_body:
There is still a lot of work here: - [x] Refactor and profile `DisplayManager` - [x] Widgets (Separate task) All widgets must be created during DrapeEngine creation. If we don't create a compass for AA -> it won't be visible on the device - [x] Fix problem with runtime DPI changes (Separate task) - [x] Create foreground service for AA (Separate task) A service created in `NavigationCarAppService` is temporary. - [x] Hide all controls on the device when AA is active - [x] Strings and translations - [x] Better icons for car and mobile phone `ic_car_connected.xml` contains an icon from [Maki Icons](https://labs.mapbox.com/maki-icons/)
Some examples

Demo:

https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/10351358/233177820-8cd59c18-51cf-4fb0-a442-1b2ecd3f1642.mp4

There are a lot of bugs on DHU's or Car Library's side. Not mine üòÑ 
I hope it will work correctly on real devices. I also saw the same bugs in other apps, f.e. maps.me.

Search screen:
* 0:10 - distance and opening hours are shown for the suggestion. If you check the code, you'll find it's not possible.
* 0:14 - 0:18  - distance and opening hours are displayed two times and even have different values for one search result
* 0:38 - 0:44 - search text is not updated when I click on the suggestion

SearchOnMap screen:
* same problems for distance and opening hours.

I circled all places that were displayed incorrectly with the mouse.

Also, don't check the logic of SearchOnMap screen very carefully. It's just a template and better implementation should be done. I'll prepare a separate issue for this screen.

I'm opening a new screen and still see the old one for some time. I'm trying to click buttons on the old screen and nothing happens. That's how it works. I can't say whether this is a bug or a "feature" but here are my thoughts on how it works. I guess they have to separate queues for pushing/popping a Screen and for handling button clicks. Now, the main thread is free and a new screen is displayed. The screen queue is empty and the button queue is being processed. There is an action stored in the button queue (click on the old screen). And it's applied even if the new screen is displayed. In simple use-case that should never happen but we have the `PopToRoot` hack that brings some troubles üòÑ ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 5, 19, 10, 52, 43, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'AndrewShkrob', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1198832401, 'comment_body': "Unfortunately, that's the only possible way to extend the default `Action.BACK` with custom logic. It's used only in `PlaceScreen` and probably won't be used anywhere else but I don't want to store this class together with `PlaceScreen` in a single file. There are already a lot of code and will be even more.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 5, 19, 10, 56, 29, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'AndrewShkrob', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1198832873, 'comment_body': 'Check the answer in [android/src/app/organicmaps/car/util/UiHelpers.java](https://github.com/organicmaps/organicmaps/pull/5045/files/833879d9d1d09a5e41ac1fc8840703e27dd7085e#diff-49a3cc630c3be3988531c49a1f8d736da45d3fce38f380433ebe340d79602931)', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 5, 19, 10, 57, 4, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'AndrewShkrob', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1198835164, 'comment_body': "I don't think it's a good idea to combine the logic of two separate modules - a car and a regular app. And I don't think that it's possible.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 5, 19, 11, 0, 11, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'AndrewShkrob', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1198869601, 'comment_body': 'It's really hard to explain but I'll try. The main problem is that we're limited to 6 (or 5, I don't remember) screens in the stack. The 6th(5th) one can only be a navigation template. So, we can create only 5 screens. Looks like it should be enough and we'll never need more. But the thing is that one screen can be treated as 2 or more during the information updates on it. It depends on the template and on the information being updated. The description can be checked on the docs page for each template. Example for `MapTemplate`: https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/car/app/navigation/model/MapTemplate >Template Restrictions In regards to template refreshes, as described in [onGetTemplate](https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/car/app/Screen#onGetTemplate()), this template is considered a refresh of a previous one if: >* The template title has not changed, and the number of rows and the title (not counting spans) of each row between the previous and new [Pane](https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/car/app/model/Pane)s or [ItemList](https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/car/app/model/ItemList)s have not changed. This `MapTemplate` is used on `PlaceScreen`. So, imagine the workflow: * You are on the main screen (screen stack size: 1) * You go to search (screen stack size: 2) * You got then to interactive search (screen stack size: 3) * You go to place screen (screen stack size: 4) * You click the "build route" button. The route is built and the screen is refreshed (added a new row with the info about route length and time). According to the template restrictions, this refresh will be considered as a new screen. (screen stack size: 5) We already reached the limit. * What if we want to change the routing settings? It's not good to drop all the progress (all these screens), go to the main screen, then to settings and so on. So, we have a settings button on this screen. If we click - we'll have 6 screens in the stack. That's not possible. * Another case. We support multiple routes. And one more screen will be to select the track. It's also not possible. * Or one more case. We want to go to another place and select it on the map. It also will be considered as a new screen, so 6 screens in the stack again. That's why we have to pop all previous screens when we push the new `PlaceScreen`. That means when we go back from this screen, we'll pop directly to the main screen. All search screens will be lost. That's not very convenient but that's the only way. And now to the question "Why do we need this `PopToRootHack` and why can't we just call `ScreenManager.popToRoot()`?" Imagine the case: You're on a search screen and you select the place. What should be called? ```java ScreenManager.popToRoot(); ScreenManager.push(new PlaceScreen(...)); ``` What should happen? The screens stack should be cleaned and a new screen should be pushed to the stack. At the end, the stack size should be equal to 2: root screen and place screen. And that's how it works üòÜ But there is one problem. There are TWO stacks: one for the screen objects (and it's size will be 2, as I wrote above) and another one (let's call it the callstack). The second stack represents the screens that were displayed. When we call `popToRoot` and `push` together, the root screen won't be displayed, we will see only the pushed screen. So, the callstack won't be popped to 1 and increased to 2 like the screens stack. It just will be increased to 4 (or 5). That's why we need a `PopToRootHack`. It works like a screen. Just `screenManager.push(new PopToRootHack)`. How it works inside? It will popToRoot and wait until the main thread is free (that means the root screen is already displayed) and then it will push our desired screen. So we will have screens stack and callstack in a consistent state. The same shit happens when you're already on a `PlaceScreen` and you select another one on the map. We need to popToRoot (with hack) first and only after this we are able to push a new `PlaceScreen`. Otherwise, it will be considered as a new callstack entry. I hope you understood something.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 5, 19, 11, 45, 44, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'AndrewShkrob', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1198872661, 'comment_body': "You can see this callstack in the bottom right corner on the demo. It's a `steps` section.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 5, 19, 11, 49, 33, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'AndrewShkrob', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1198876452, 'comment_body': '–Ø –≤ —ç—Ç–æ–º –≤–∞—à–µ–º Android Auto —É–∂–µ –Ω–∞—Å—Ç–æ–ª—å–∫–æ –ø—Ä–µ–∏—Å–ø–æ–ª–Ω–∏–ª—Å—è, —á—Ç–æ —è –∫–∞–∫ –±—É–¥—Ç–æ –±—ã —É–∂–µ —Å—Ç–æ —Ç—Ä–∏–ª–ª–∏–æ–Ω–æ–≤ –º–∏–ª–ª–∏–∞—Ä–¥–æ–≤ –ª–µ—Ç –ø—Ä–æ–∂–∏–≤–∞—é –Ω–∞ —Ç—Ä–∏–ª–ª–∏–æ–Ω–∞—Ö –∏ —Ç—Ä–∏–ª–ª–∏–æ–Ω–∞—Ö —Ç–∞–∫–∏—Ö –∂–µ –ø–ª–∞–Ω–µ—Ç, –∫–∞–∫ —ç—Ç–∞ –ó–µ–º–ª—è, –º–Ω–µ —ç—Ç–æ—Ç –º–∏—Ä –∞–±—Å–æ–ª—é—Ç–Ω–æ –ø–æ–Ω—è—Ç–µ–Ω, –∏ —è –∑–¥–µ—Å—å –∏—â—É —Ç–æ–ª—å–∫–æ –æ–¥–Ω–æ–≥–æ - –ø–æ–∫–æ—è, —É–º–∏—Ä–æ—Ç–≤–æ—Ä–µ–Ω–∏—è –∏ –≤–æ—Ç —ç—Ç–æ–π –≥–∞—Ä–º–æ–Ω–∏–∏, –æ—Ç —Å–ª–∏—è–Ω–∏—è —Å –±–µ—Å–∫–æ–Ω–µ—á–Ω–æ –≤–µ—á–Ω—ã–º, –æ—Ç —Å–æ–∑–µ—Ä—Ü–∞–Ω–∏—è –≤–µ–ª–∏–∫–æ–≥–æ —Ñ—Ä–∞–∫—Ç–∞–ª—å–Ω–æ–≥–æ –ø–æ–¥–æ–±–∏—è –∏ –æ—Ç –≤–æ—Ç —ç—Ç–æ–≥–æ –∑–∞–º–µ—á–∞—Ç–µ–ª—å–Ω–æ–≥–æ –≤—Å–µ–µ–¥–∏–Ω—Å—Ç–≤–∞ —Å—É—â–µ—Å—Ç–≤–∞, –±–µ—Å–∫–æ–Ω–µ—á–Ω–æ –≤–µ—á–Ω–æ–≥–æ, –∫—É–¥–∞ –Ω–∏ –ø–æ—Å–º–æ—Ç—Ä–∏, —Ö–æ—Ç—å –≤–≥–ª—É–±—å - –±–µ—Å–∫–æ–Ω–µ—á–Ω–æ –º–∞–ª–æ–µ, —Ö–æ—Ç—å –≤–≤—ã—Å—å - –±–µ—Å–∫–æ–Ω–µ—á–Ω–æ–µ –±–æ–ª—å—à–æ–µ, –ø–æ–Ω–∏–º–∞–µ—à—å? ![image](https://github.com/organicmaps/organicmaps/assets/10351358/7ddf4383-3940-4892-a508-adf791c5c791) ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 5, 19, 11, 54, 36, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'AndrewShkrob', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1199418008, 'comment_body': "I don't know :) That needs to be checked and tested. Let's leave it for now.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 5, 19, 21, 30, 17, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'AndrewShkrob', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1199652592, 'comment_body': 'With max 5 templates in a stack the whole UX should be simplified and done differently. Will ot work on non-touch devices?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 5, 20, 19, 47, 1, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'biodranik', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1199752593, 'comment_body': "> With max 5 templates in a stack the whole UX should be simplified and done differently. I gave you an example of the workflow with search. Any ideas on how to make it simple? > Is it possible to make a (simplified) diagram of the whole UX, including screens and user actions? Yes, it's possible. But I don't see any sense to spend time on it. It won't help us to decrease the number of templates in the stack. > Can we make it as simple as possible to get a release ASAP From my pov, it's already as simple as possible. We support only the features that are required during the navigation with AA. I'm pretty sure that simplification (in our case) will harm the UX. > Will ot work on non-touch devices? Again, yes. Btw, Yandex.Maps uses the same approach.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 5, 21, 11, 58, 3, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'AndrewShkrob', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1199770494, 'comment_body': "OK, I see.
